<section class="info-section animate-fade" style="animation-delay: 0.2s;">
  <h2 class="text-gradient">Kitchen & Fridge Guide</h2>
  <p class="section-desc">Recommended foods to stock your fridge for optimal health and goal meeting.</p>

  <div class="info-grid">
    <div class="info-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Proteins">ü•¨</div>
      <h3>Proteins</h3>
      <p>Building blocks for muscles and repair. Aim for lean sources.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> Chicken breast, tofu, eggs, Greek yogurt (plain), salmon, turkey.</li>
        <li><strong>Tip:</strong> Aim for 1.6g-2g per kg of body weight if you are active.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Carbohydrates">üåæ</div>
      <h3>Carbohydrates</h3>
      <p>Primary energy source. Focus on "Complex" over "Simple".</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> Pre-cooked quinoa, brown rice, sweet potatoes, hummus.</li>
        <li><strong>Focus:</strong> "Long" (Complex) carbs provide steady energy. "Simple" (Sugar) leads to crashes.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Healthy Fats">ü•ë</div>
      <h3>Healthy Fats</h3>
      <p>Essential for hormones and brain health. Balance Saturated vs Unsaturated.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> Avocado, walnuts, olive oil (pantry), flax seeds, chia pudding.</li>
        <li><strong>LDL Goal:</strong> Keep saturated fats (found in cheese, red meat) low to lower bad cholesterol.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Vitamins and Fiber">üçé</div>
      <h3>Vitamins & Fiber</h3>
      <p>The UK "5 A Day" rule (approx. 400g total) is the minimum. Aim for variety in colors.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fridge:</strong> Spinach, kale, berries, carrots, bell peppers, broccoli.</li>
        <li><strong>Health:</strong> Fiber is crucial for gut health and lowering sugar spikes.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-gradient" style="margin-top: 4rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;"><span role="img" aria-label="Warning">‚ö†Ô∏è</span> Critical Limitations & Health Alerts</h2>
  <p class="section-desc">Important knowledge to avoid common health pitfalls and toxic loads.</p>

  <div class="info-grid">
    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Red Meat">ü•©</div>
      <h3>Red Meat Limits</h3>
      <p>Red meat (Beef, Lamb, Pork) is nutrient-dense but linked to bowel cancer if over-consumed.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Limit:</strong> &lt; 500g (cooked weight) per week. That's about 2-3 steaks max.</li>
        <li><strong>Risk:</strong> Eating 1kg+ per week significantly increases inflammation and cancer risk.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Processed Meats">üå≠</div>
      <h3>Processed Meats & Nitrates</h3>
      <p>The "Dirty List" of cancer-linked foods due to Nitrates/Nitrites used for curing.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Avoid:</strong> Bacon, Salami, Ham, Hot Dogs, Pepperoni.</li>
        <li><strong>Why:</strong> Group 1 Carcinogens (WHO). They damage DNA in the gut. Treat as a rare treat, not a staple.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Ultra-Processed Foods">üè≠</div>
      <h3>Ultra-Processed Foods (UPF)</h3>
      <p>Industrial formulations with 5+ ingredients you wouldn't find in a home kitchen.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Identify:</strong> Emulsifiers, gums, artificial flavors, high fructose corn syrup.</li>
        <li><strong>Impact:</strong> Linked to overeating, obesity, and metabolic disease. Eat "Whole Foods" instead.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Pesticides">üçì</div>
      <h3>The "Dirty Dozen" (Pesticides)</h3>
      <p>Fruits/Veggies that retain the most pesticides. Buy <strong>Organic</strong> for these if possible:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>List:</strong> Strawberries, Spinach, Kale, Nectarines, Apples, Grapes.</li>
        <li><strong>Alternative:</strong> The "Clean Fifteen" (Avocados, Onions) are safer to buy conventionally grown.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Fish">üêü</div>
      <h3>Fish: Mercury vs Health</h3>
      <p>Fish is great for Omega-3, but some accumulate heavy metals.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Limit:</strong> Large predators (Shark, Swordfish, King Mackerel) due to high Mercury.</li>
        <li><strong>Smoked Fish:</strong> Delicious but often very high in sodium. Limit if monitoring Blood Pressure.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="info-card warning-card">
      <div class="icon" role="img" aria-label="Dairy">üßÄ</div>
      <h3>Dairy & Cottage Cheese</h3>
      <p>Excellent protein source (casein), but quality matters.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cottage Cheese:</strong> Superb lean protein, but check <strong>Sodium</strong> levels.</li>
        <li><strong>Full Fat:</strong> OK in moderation, but limit saturated fat intake if your LDL cholesterol is high.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

